    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.17.17-19_0001"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">17</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">BENJAMIN DECASSERES</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>July 15/37</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Thanks so much for your cordial letter. I can "dish it out," so I have learned "to take it," as our poetic youngsters say. I never kick against an honest <unclear>slam in</unclear> the slots&#8212; <del/><add>and</add> Jesus knows I'm a man of many faults, blemishes, <unclear/> and all that, both personally and in my writing. <hi rend="underline">But</hi> (and this is a common mistake made about me) I am utterly <add>without</add>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.17.17-19_0002"/>
                <fw type="curatorial">18</fw>
                
                    pose, as anyone who knows me will tell the world. My writings are the man, the man is <add>my</add> writing. I note that in this queer world (particularly in this blessed country of ours) that when a man is utterly himself, just natural, he is said to be "different" (which of course he <hi rend="underline">is</hi>!), "freakish" and <add>is</add> trying "to put something over." In a word, any form of sincerity that involves "difference" or originality is denounced as "fake" in a world that lives, moves, and has its <unclear reason="faded"/> in show. But you know all this.</p>
                
                <p>When you write about
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.17.17-19_0003"/>
                <fw type="curatorial">19</fw>
                
                    me next fall (if you do) tear the guts out of me if you will (and no hard feelings), but if you say my work is insincere or a "mannered pose"&#8212;well, you will be absolutely wrong.</p>
                
                <p>Well, that's off my chest &#8212; and, like the human race in general, it is of no importance.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Good wishes to you,</salute>
                    <signed>Benjamin DeCasseres</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
